SIMPLE: linger
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Linger
<hw>Lin"ger</hw> <pr>(l⟦icr⟧⟦nsm⟧"g⟦etil⟧r)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Lingered</conjf>
<pr>(l⟦icr⟧⟦nsm⟧"g⟦etil⟧rd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Lingering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>lengen</ets> to
tarry, AS. <ets>lengan</ets> to prolong, put off, fr. <ets>lang</ets>
long. ⟦root⟧125. See <er>Long</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <def>To delay;
to loiter; to remain or wait long; to be slow or reluctant in parting or
moving; to be slow in deciding; to be in suspense; to
hesitate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nor cast one longing, <qex>lingering</qex> look behind.</q>
<rj><qau>Gray.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Perhaps thou <qex>linger'st</qex>, in deep thoughts detained.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To loiter; lag; saunter; delay; tarry; stop;
hesitate.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Linger</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Linger
<hw>Lin"ger</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To protract; to draw
out.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She <qex>lingers</qex> my desires.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To spend or pass in a lingering manner; -- with
<xex>out</xex>; <as>as, to <ex>linger</ex> out one's days on a sick
bed</as>.</def> <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lingerer</ent>⟦br⟧
